ding:0px;\">\r\n			<span class=\"a-text-bold\" style=\"font-weight:700 !important;\">Answer:</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"a-fixed-left-grid-col a-col-right\" style=\"margin:0px;padding:0px;\">\r\n			<span>I was actually surprised how well it charged in the house. So well I had to turn it so the solar panel was not exposed. I am not sure how many hours of charge it received in this manner.</span>&nbsp;<br />\r\n<span class=\"a-color-tertiary\" style=\"color:#767676 !important;\">By Alaria Sun on January 4, 2017</span><span class=\"askInlineAnswers\" id=\"Tx3RNYVR6V23HT0\">\r\n			<div id=\"askInlineAnswersPage-Tx3RNYVR6V23HT0-1\" class=\"a-section a-spacing-none\" style=\"margin:0px;padding:0px;\">\r\n				<div class=\"a-section a-spacing-none a-spacing-top-small\" style=\"margin:0px;padding:0px;\">\r\n					<span class=\"askExpanderContainer askExpanderExpanded\">Until it quits snowing, I have the light with the solar cells facing outdoors in a window that gets occasional sun and when it does it generally works all night. If it is cloudy, the light quits working about 3 or 4am. If indoor lighting is bright enough to switch off the LEDs then the unit will charge a little but not enough to run all night. I\'m sure that when I get this unit mounted come spring, the light will work, sun or clouds, long enough into the evening to light the way for people to come and go.</span><br />\r\n<span class=\"a-color-tertiary\" style=\"color:#767676 !important;\">By James D. Anderson on January 4, 2017</span>\r\n				</div>\r\n			</div>\r\n</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n	</div>\r\n	<div id=\"question-TxCQP824KNKVY4\" class=\"a-fixed-left-grid a-spacing-small\" style=\"margin:0px;padding:0px;\">\r\n		<div class=\"a-fixed-left-grid-inner\" style=\"margin:0px;padding:0px 0px 0px 100px;\">\r\n			<div class=\"a-fixed-left-grid-col a-col-left\" style=\"margin:0px 0px 0px -100px;padding:0px;\">\r\n				<span class=\"a-text-bold\" style=\"font-weight:700 !important;\">Question:</span>\r\n			</